{"title_page": "The Square (2008 film)", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Square\n| image          = The_square_film.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Nash Edgerton]]\n| producer       = Louise Smith\n| writer         = [[Joel Edgerton]]<br />Matthew Dabner\n| starring       = [[David Roberts (Australian actor)|David Roberts]]<br />[[Claire van der Boom]]<br />Joel Edgerton<br />[[Anthony Hayes (actor)|Anthony Hayes]]<br />[[Peter Phelps]]<br />[[Bill Hunter (actor)|Bill Hunter]]\n| music          = [[Fran\u00e7ois T\u00e9taz|Frank Tetaz]]<br />[[Ben Lee]]\n| cinematography = Brad Shield\n| editing        = [[Luke Doolan]]<br>Nash Edgerton\n| studio         = [[Path\u00e9]]<br />[[Blue-Tongue Films]]<br />Film Depot<br />[[Film Australia|FFC Australia]]\n| distributor    = [[Village Roadshow Limited]]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|2008|6|15|Sydney Film Festival|2008|07|31|Australia}}\n| runtime        = 107 minutes\n| country        = Australia\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n| gross          = \n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n'''''The Square''''' is a 2008 Australian [[neo-noir]] [[thriller film]] directed by [[Nash Edgerton]], written by his brother [[Joel Edgerton]] and Matthew Dabner, and starring [[David Roberts (Australian actor)|David Roberts]] and [[Claire van der Boom]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The Square|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/films.php?id=61365|accessdate=17 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Square by filmmakers Nash and Joel Edgerton|url=http://www.landmarktheatres.com/letters/square.htm|accessdate=17 July 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108095458/http://www.landmarktheatres.com/letters/square.htm|archivedate=8 November 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Based upon an original idea by Joel, the project was written and then shelved by the actor because he felt it was not strong enough. It was only made after his director brother Nash read the script and convinced him it could be filmed as a thriller.<ref name=\"d\">{{cite web|title=Joel Edgerton, Actor, writer, star of \"The Square\" On \"The Square\" Root Of Agony And Chaos|url=http://www.popcornreel.com/htm/joeledgerton.html|accessdate=17 July 2013}}</ref> The film premiered in competition at [[Sydney Film Festival]] on 15 June 2008<ref name=\"b\" /> and after that had a limited release in Australia on 31 July 2008, and was released in North America in 2010 by [[Apparition (company)|Apparition]].<ref name=\"d\" />\n\n==Plot==\nRaymond Yale ([[David Roberts (Australian actor)|David Roberts]]) and Carla Smith ([[Claire van der Boom]]) are lovers in a small Australian town living across the river from one another. However, both are already married; Raymond to a loveless wife and Carla to a domineering petty gangster Greg \"Smithy\" Smith ([[Anthony Hayes (actor)|Anthony Hayes]]). Ray and Carla plan to leave their respective spouses and run away together, although Ray insists that they delay until he has enough money to ensure a new life together. As a foreman overseeing the construction of a new leisure resort for property developer Gil Hubbard ([[Bill Hunter (actor)|Bill Hunter]]), Ray has been doing underhanded deals with construction worker Barney ([[Kieran Darcy-Smith]]) for the hefty kick-backs which he hopes will eventually land him enough to run off with Carla.\n\nIn the meantime, Ray and Carla are forced to conduct their affair in secret, occasionally made awkward by meeting each other at local events and by Carla's dog periodically escaping and instinctively running to Ray's house to meet his dog. One day, after returning home from work, Carla sees Smithy wiping blood off his hands and stashing a [[money bag|duffel bag full of cash]] into their ceiling; presumably the loot from an armed robbery conducted by Smithy's gang. Carla tells Ray, insisting this to be the end of their financial troubles, and although he is initially hesitant she finally persuades him to steal the money.\n\nRay devises a plan. He will need to burn the house down so Smithy thinks the money was simply destroyed rather than stolen, a job for which he hires the local arsonist, Billy ([[Joel Edgerton]]). Carla will first steal the money from the hiding place and then Billy will arrive and set a fire to make it look as though it was caused by faulty Christmas tree lights.\n\nWhile the whole town is at the Christmas celebration, Carla sneaks back to the house and takes the money from the duffel bag. However, on return she overhears Smithy phoning his mother and asking her to go to his house (the one Billy is planning to burn down) and feed his dog. Carla alerts Ray who quickly tries to ring Billy, but is only able to reach his sister Lily ([[Hanna Mangan-Lawrence]]). With his phone dying, Ray tells Lily to abort the plan but Lily is unable to alert Billy before he leaves. Billy breaks in and sets the fire, unaware of Smithy's mum sleeping on the lounge. Consequently, she dies in the ensuing blaze.\n\nThus things begin to take a downward slide for Ray and Carla. Lily neglects to tell Billy about Ray's call aborting the plan, causing Billy to think he has been duped unwillingly into murdering an old lady. Smithy, devastated by his mother's death, then discovers that the money had, in fact, been stolen, and begins to search ruthlessly for the culprits. And Ray's life is further complicated when someone starts sending him Christmas cards threatening to reveal \"what you're up to\" unless a $10,000 blackmail is paid. What follows is a quickening spiral of murder, suspicion, violence and deceit with shocking consequences for the two lovers and everyone around them. Every time someone discovers something about Ray, they end up dead in some accident caused by Ray trying to stop them. The blackmailer is discovered to be Barney and his wife (who have been scamming people by providing kick-backs and then blackmailing them). Ray goes to Carla's house so they can run off together only to find Billy. Billy demands the rest of his money and Carla gives him the bag full of money she and Ray were going to run away with. As Billy forces Ray and Carla on their knees, Smithy walks in and pulls a gun on Billy. In the fire exchange Smithy is killed and as Ray tries to take the gun from Billy, Carla is shot in the head. Billy leaves as Ray weeps over Carla's body. Ray walks off down the road in shock from the events.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[David Roberts (Australian actor)|David Roberts]] as Raymond Yale\n*[[Claire van der Boom]] as Carla Smith\n*[[Joel Edgerton]] as Billy\n*[[Anthony Hayes (actor)|Anthony Hayes]] as Greg \"Smithy\" Smith\n*[[Hanna Mangan-Lawrence]] as Lily\n*[[Peter Phelps]] as Jake\n*[[Kieran Darcy-Smith]] as Barney\n*Brendan Donoghue as Leonard Long\n*[[Damon Herriman]] as Eddie\n*[[Bill Hunter (actor)|Bill Hunter]] as Gil Hubbard\n*[[Julian Morrow]] as Dale\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development===\nJoel Edgerton wrote the script in eight years.<ref name=\"d\" /> He said that \"I first wrote \"The Square\" as an idea in my early 20s just, I had notebooks filled with thoughts and ideas about movies I wanted to write, but I never was a writer until I sat down to write a screenplay for Nash. It was this sort of jumbled mess of a thing I was trying to write for him, a crime caper story. As I started writing that, I sort of stopped at one point and started writing \"The Square\" as a different project with no director attached to it. Then at some point, when \"The Square\" started developing its first draft and then at subsequent drafts, I eventually did the old Indiana Jones switcharoo and was like, \"Why don't we just take this script away and put this one in its place because I think this is a more mature project for us to make.\" Thankfully, he felt the same and so we basically put our focus into a new thing and that became The Square.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Exclusive: Joel Edgerton Digs into The Square|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=64854|accessdate=17 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nFilming took place in late 2007 at [[Sutherland, New South Wales|Sutherland]], [[Cronulla, New South Wales|Cronulla]] and [[Caringbah, New South Wales|Caringbah]] the [[suburb]]s of [[New South Wales]], [[Australia]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Director Nash Edgerton and Joel Edgerton Interview THE SQUARE|url=http://collider.com/director-nash-edgerton-and-joel-edgerton-interview-the-square/|accessdate=17 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critical response===\nThe film received positive reviews from critics. [[Review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reports that 86% out of 85 professional critics gave the film a positive review, with a rating average of 7.25/10 and the critical consensus being: \"The Square may not quite live up to the modern noir classics that inspired it, but with twists and tension to spare, it comes admirably close.\"<ref>[http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/square/ The Square]. ''Rotten Tomatoes''. [[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]. Retrieved 25 July 2019.</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' gave three-and-a-half stars out of four and said that \"it never pushes too hard or moves too fast. It lovingly, almost sadistically, lays out the situation and deliberately demonstrates all the things that can go wrong. And I mean all the things.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Crime doesn't pay|url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-square-2010|accessdate=17 July 2013}}</ref> Dan Kois of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' praised Edgerton brother's and said that \"the debut feature of Nash and Joel Edgerton, Australian actors-turned-filmmakers, calls to mind another great darkly comic debut, the [[Coen brothers]]' ''[[Blood Simple]]''. Like that movie, ''The Square'' uses the trappings of film noir to explore a moral universe in which connivers and crooks are their own worst enemies. And like ''Blood Simple'', ''The Square'' suggests an exciting future for a pair of brothers with a dark view of pitiless fate.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Movie review: 'The Square,' a finely tuned Australian thriller|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/05/06/AR2010050602329.html|accessdate=17 July 2013 | work=The Washington Post|first=Dan|last=Kois|date=7 May 2010}}</ref> Lou Lumenick of the ''[[New York Post]]'' in his review said that \"A starless but highly effective Aussie noir that marks the auspicious feature debut of stuntman and music-video director Nash Edgerton.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Sinner takes all|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/entertainment/movies/sinner_takes_all_LMceoFBTywBnYeviKcn3iL|accessdate=17 July 2013 | work=New York Post|first=Lou|last=Lumenick}}</ref>\n\nMoira Macdonald of ''[[The Seattle Times]]'' gave the film two-and-a-half stars out of four; however, she criticised the script by saying that \"Indeed, there's a bit of everything in ''The Square'', so much so that after a while it starts to feel generic.\"<ref>{{cite web|title='The Square': Shape of things to come from first-time director Nash Edgerton?|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/movies/2011678022_mr23square.html|accessdate=17 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\n''The Square'' grossed $321,788 at the box office in Australia in 2008.<ref>[http://film.vic.gov.au/resources/documents/AA4_Aust_Box_office_report.pdf ''Film Victoria - Australian Films at the Australian Box Office''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723234802/http://film.vic.gov.au/resources/documents/AA4_Aust_Box_office_report.pdf |date=23 July 2011 }}</ref> In 2010, it was released in the [[United States|U.S.]] in 24 theatres (spending 105 days in release) and grossed $406,116.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Square|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=square10.htm|accessdate=17 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n''The Square'' was released on DVD with Edgerton's short film [[Spider (2007 film)|''Spider'']], on 24 August 2010.<ref>{{cite news|title=This Week\u2019s Short Film \u2013 Spider|url=http://filmbalaya.com/2011/01/16/this-weeks-short-film-spider/|date=30 April 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130912125901/http://filmbalaya.com/2011/01/16/this-weeks-short-film-spider/|archivedate=12 September 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The Square (2008)|url=http://www.ondvdreleases.com/864-the-square-dvd-release-date.html|date=30 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Awards===\n''The Square'' won a commendation in the 'Best Australian Film' category of the [[Australian Film Critics Association]] awards for 2008.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Recipient\n! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"16\"| 2008\n| Australian Screen Directors Guild Awards\n| Best Direction in a Feature Film\n| [[Nash Edgerton]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[ARIA Music Awards]]\n| [[ARIA Music Awards of 2008#Best Original Soundtrack / Cast / Show Album|Best Original Soundtrack Album]]\n| [[Ben Lee]]<br>Nic Johns<br>[[Jessica Chapnik]]\n| {{nom}}<ref>{{cite web|title= 2008 ARIA Awards Nominees Announced... And Here They Are!|url=http://www.undercover.fm/news/6197-2008-aria-awards-nominees-announced-and-here-they-are|accessdate=17 July 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"7\"| [[Australian Film Institute]]\n| [[AACTA Award for Best Direction|Best Direction]]\n| [[Nash Edgerton]]\n| {{nom}}<ref name=\"n\">{{cite web|title=2008 AFI Awards Nominees|url=http://www.afi.org.au/AM/ContentManagerNet/HTMLDisplay.aspx?ContentID=5931&Section=AFI_Awards_Nominees|accessdate=17 July 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090914100500/http://www.afi.org.au/AM/ContentManagerNet/HTMLDisplay.aspx?ContentID=5931&Section=AFI_Awards_Nominees|archivedate=14 September 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[AACTA Award for Best Film|Best Film]]\n| Louise Smith\n| {{nom}}<ref name=\"n\" />\n|-\n| [[AACTA Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role|Best Lead Acto